One might object that they do not wish to tamper with their natural sleep, even if melatonin is a normally-secreted hormone.

Sad to say, I would point out to such readers that they are *already* profoundly tampering with their natural sleep cycle, and indeed, all of Western civilization is tampering with it; most of my readers do not even sleep multiple times during the day, as 'Nature intends' and as humans have usually slept through history[^Ekirch][^Stampi], but rather in a single 7-9 hour long block. [Sleep debt](!Wikipedia) causes negative changes similar to [aging](http://jvsmedicscorner.com/Physiology_files/Impact%20of%20sleep%20debt%20on%20metabolic%20and%20endocrine%20function.pdf "'Impact of sleep debt on metabolic and endocrine function', Spiegel et al 1999"), and [sleep deprivation](!Wikipedia), both acute [*and* chronic](http://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2010/08/100809161230.htm), damage mental performance[^daylight-savings], and chronic does so [cumulatively](https://web.archive.org/web/20131203133939/http://web2.med.upenn.edu/uep/user_documents/dfd16.pdf "'The cumulative cost of additional wakefulness: dose-response effects on neurobehavioral functions and sleep physiology from chronic sleep restriction and total sleep deprivation', Van Dongen et al 2003") over the deprivation period (conversely, sleep [improves performance](http://blogs.hbr.org/schwartz/2011/03/sleep-is-more-important-than-f.html)); worse, one may not be able to simply sleep in on the weekend, both because it's too short a time period to repay sleep debt ([Dement 2005](/docs/melatonin/2005-dement.html.maff "Sleep extension: getting as much extra sleep as possible") noting it may take a full month to repay the large sleep debt incurred by regular shortfalls; [jet lag](!Wikipedia) in well-rested mice can take [up to 28 days](http://www.plosone.org/article/info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0015267 "'Experimental `Jet Lag` Inhibits Adult Neurogenesis and Produces Long-Term Cognitive Deficits in Female Hamsters', Gibson et al 2010") to mentally recover from) and because in practice one *doesn't* sleep in very much - the Zeo database of sleep records only [an extra 23 minutes a day](http://web.archive.org/web/20120620034226/http://blog.myzeo.com/sleep-by-night-of-the-week/) on the weekend. Subjects in chronic sleep deprivation studies subject to [sleep debt](!Wikipedia) were subjectively [unable to notice their performance declines](http://www.med.upenn.edu/uep/user_documents/VanDongen_etal_Sleep_26_2_2003.pdf "'The Cumulative Cost of Additional Wakefulness: Dose-Response Effects on Neurobehavioral Functions and Sleep Physiology From Chronic Sleep Restriction and Total Sleep Deprivation', Dongen et al 2003") ([_NYT_](http://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/17/magazine/mag-17Sleep-t.html "How Little Sleep Can You Get Away With?")); and since "short sleepers" seem [little different from everyone else](https://web.archive.org/web/20121202034036/http://www.sciencesleep.org/ziliao/A%20sleep%20diary%20and%20questionnaire%20study%20of%20naturally%20short%20sleepers.pdf "'A sleep diary and questionnaire study of naturally short sleepers', Monk et al 2001"), this suggests that many people who believe they are short sleepers are just [hurting](http://postcog.ucd.ie/files/Hrrison%20and%20horne.pdf "'The Impact of Sleep Deprivation on Decision Making: A Review', Harrison & Horne 2000") [themselves](http://faculty.vet.upenn.edu/uep/user_documents/dfd3.pdf "'Neurocognitive Consequences of Sleep Deprivation', Durmer & Dinges 2005"). Finally, there are multiple lines of research suggesting chronic sleep deprivation is prevalent among [young adults](http://www.soundersleep.com/uploads/Bonnet-Arand.pdf) (including historical comparisons^[See Webb WB, Agnew HW (1975), "Are we chronically sleep deprived?" _Bull. the Psychonomic_ Soc. 6:47-48.]^[["Never Enough Sleep: A Brief History of Sleep Recommendations for Children"](/docs/melatonin/2012-matricciani.pdf "Matricciani et al 2012") reviews literature from 2009 back to 1897, finding that sleep fell by around an hour on average (with very wide variation at both dates); they also find that sleep recommendations are regularly anchored towards recommending more sleep than children were actually getting - which the authors apparently take as evidence for the recommendations being false but I take as perfectly consistent with the picture I illustrate here of an ever more short-sleeping modern society and explicable by the fact that the *average* of the 1890s sleep recommendations - *10.8* hours - would be hysterically laughed at by modern parents (hence the average recommendation in the 2000s of closer to 9.8 hours).]). It is striking that unemployed adults sleep a full hour longer than the employed^["A coming study by Mr. Krueger, using historical data on time use between 1991 and 2006, finds that unemployed Americans tend to sleep an hour longer than the employed." ["Leisure Trumps Learning in Time-Use Survey: Americans Opt for TV in Spare Hours, Not Workouts or Classes, Poll Finds"](http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052702304657804576401890078537246.html), 23 June 2011 _Wall Street Journal_], and that when normal adults are placed in settings without artificial light [like camping](/docs/melatonin/2013-wright.pdf "'Entrainment of the Human Circadian Clock to the Natural Light-Dark Cycle', Wright et al 2013") or without any time indicators, they sleep longer than before - exactly as if they were sleep deprived.[^arctic] Additional sleep is linked with athletic[^Ericsson-NYT] and artistic success[^Ericsson-PDF], that even a hour's tampering with melatonin secretion leads to [measurable performance changes](/docs/melatonin/2012-burgess.pdf "Can small shifts in circadian phase affect performance?"), melatonin secretion declines markedly with age, and so on and so on. One could well ask with [Alexander Pushkin](!Wikipedia), ["Why am I to feel this pain?"](http://www.russianlegacy.com/en/go_to/culture/poetry/pushkin/insomnia.htm "Verses, composed during a night of insomnia...")

